    <div class="kicker">
      <time class="updated" datetime="2008-01-22T07:51:00+00:00">Tuesday, January 22, 2008</time>
    </div>
    <h1 class="title" >
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/01/tomorrow-tomorrow/">Tomorrow, tomorrow</a>
    </h1>
  </header>
  <div class="post-content" itemprop="articleBody">
    <p>I had big plans. I was going to serve you a real whopper of a dessert today. It was going to be the butterscotch budino from <a href="http://www.mozza-la.com/pizzeria/about.cfm">Pizzeria Mozza</a>, if you really want to know, the dessert that <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/09/dining/09mozz.html?pagewanted=1&amp;sq=mozza&amp;scp=5">Frank Bruni</a> calls ‚Äúa pudding to shame all other puddings.‚Äù  (Isn‚Äôt that that the single best line of praise <span style="font-style:italic;">ever</span>? I want someone to call <span style="font-style:italic;">me</span><span style="font-style:italic;"> </span>‚Äúa pudding to shame all other puddings.‚Äù)  It was going to be <span>great</span>.</p>
<p>Have you heard about it, this butterscotch budino?  I first learned of it when <a href="http://wednesdaychef.typepad.com/the_wednesday_chef/2007/03/sweet_reverie.html">Luisa</a> wrote about Mozza last March, and then I went chasing the recipe, which, happily, was printed in the <span style="font-style:italic;"><a style="font-style:italic;" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/09/dining/091mrex.html?_r=1&amp;oref=slogin">New York Times</a>, </span><span>the</span><span style="font-style:italic;"> <a style="font-style:italic;" href="http://www.latimes.com/features/printedition/food/la-fow-honorrecs26dec26,0,5481277.story?page=12">Los Angeles Times</a>, </span><span>and</span><span style="font-style:italic;"> <a style="font-style:italic;" href="http://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/239847">Bon App√©tit</a><span style="font-style:italic;">, </span></span><span>each with a drool-inducing description.  It sounded heart-stoppingly good: a ramekin of rich butterscotch pudding topped with a warm caramel sauce and a hearty smattering of salt <span style="font-style:italic;">and,</span> on top of that, a dollop of cr√®me fra√Æche whipped cream.  Needless to say, I printed the <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/09/dining/091mrex.html">recipe</a> and planned to make it immediately.</p>
<p>Of course, </span>‚Äúimmediately‚Äù turned out to be this past weekend, which wasn‚Äôt so immediate, but anyway.  I made it, and despite its three separate components, it was really quite simple and painless.  (I even made the <span>cr√®me fra√Æche <a href="http://wednesdaychef.typepad.com/the_wednesday_chef/2008/01/russ-parsonss-m.html">from <span>scratch</span></a>! S</span>o much cheaper that way.<span>) But oh, I don</span>‚Äôt know.  I didn‚Äôt <span style="font-style:italic;">love</span> it. Maybe I did something wrong? Or maybe it requires a pinch of pastry chef pixie dust that the recipe forgot to mention?  The pudding was very nice, but it didn‚Äôt leave me clawing for more.  The caramel sauce was likewise tasty, but it didn‚Äôt make me feel like ripping off my clothes and bathing in it, which, let‚Äôs be honest, a really good caramel usually<span style="font-style:italic;"> </span>makes me want to do.   It wasn‚Äôt bad; I just wasn‚Äôt as excited as I wanted to be.</p>
<p>Does this make me a bad person?   A picky little twit? Or perhaps I‚Äôm just so-so when it comes to making puddings and caramels?  Maybe I‚Äôll make it again this week, just to give it the good old college try.  Or maybe I‚Äôll dig out another recipe I clipped a couple of years ago, a recipe for butterscotch pot de cr<span>√®me, and try <span style="font-style:italic;">that</span></span> instead.  Would you like that?  I certainly would.  Tomorrow, tomorrow, I love ya tomorrow.</p>
<p>Anyway, this is just to say that I had Exciting! Fun!  Plans for today, but instead, I bring you an old standby.  Not that it‚Äôs anything to sneeze at.  It‚Äôs just less flashy, that‚Äôs all.  It‚Äôs the recipe for Brandon‚Äôs quick black beans with cumin and oregano.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/24a84-blackbeans024-11.jpg"><img decoding="async" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/24a84-blackbeans024-11.jpg?w=300" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5158106648890506626" border="0" /></a><br />Much like his <a href="http://orangette.blogspot.com/2007/01/brown-bag-it.html">chickpea salad</a>, these beans are something we eat often for lunch, especially on Saturdays and Sundays, when we want to sit down and share a meal but don‚Äôt feel much like fussing.  We ate them yesterday, in fact, and in mid-chew, I thought, <span style="font-style:italic;">Gosh, I really should tell them about this</span>.  Which is more than I can say for some things.</p>
<p>I‚Äôm going to go out on a limb here, but I really do believe it: that there is great value, people, in knowing how to doctor a can of beans.  It‚Äôs nothing to be ashamed of.  It‚Äôs one of those important life skills, like knowing how to make a bed, tie your shoes, or operate a corkscrew. In this case, you just cook an onion in olive oil, add some cumin and oregano and a good splash of hot sauce, and then chuck in a can of beans, juices and all.  (I know the can juices can seem kind of yucky, but as Brandon likes to say, think of it as a broth of sorts.  Doesn‚Äôt that feel better?) It all burbles together for a few minutes, just long enough to warm through, and then it‚Äôs ready to go, earthy and spicy and faintly sweet. With a green salad on the side, or some sliced avocado, or some bread and a hunk of cheddar, or, heck, whatever‚Äôs in the fridge, these beans make a terrific, easy lunch.  Which, if you ask me, is much more important than pudding anyway.</p>
<p>Have a happy week, friends.  I‚Äôll see you on the canned beans aisle.</p>
<p>***</p>
<p>Oh, but wait!  One more thing: our <span style="font-weight:bold;">cooking class</span> on ‚Äúmisunderstood‚Äù winter vegetables &#8211; Brussels sprouts, fennel, and cauliflower &#8211; is coming up fast!   And there are still a few spots available!  The class will take place next Tuesday, <span style="font-weight:bold;">January 29</span>, in Bellingham, and is hosted and organized by <a href="http://inthekitchenbellingham.blogspot.com/">In the Kitchen</a>, a new production of Ciao Thyme, the lovely and talented people who catered our wedding.  To learn more about our vegetable class &#8211; and our eggs class on March 18 &#8211; please click <a href="http://gabrielboone.com/class_calendars/ITK_Class_Calendar_2008_Q1.pdf">here</a>.  You can sign up by e-mailing <span style="font-style:italic;">classes (at) inthekitchenbellingham (dot) com</span>, or by calling 360.733.1267.  We‚Äôre tickled, just <span style="font-style:italic;">tickled</span>, to have this chance to teach, and we really do hope to see you there.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight:bold;">Quick Black Beans with Cumin and Oregano</span></p>
<p>Canned black beans differ dramatically from brand to brand.  Brandon usually uses Trader Joe‚Äôs brand, or Bush‚Äôs, or Goya, and all are very good. Yesterday we made these beans with Western Family organic brand, and they weren‚Äôt nearly as tasty.  So be choosy about your beans.</p>
<p>Oh, and about hot sauces: you can use most any brand of Mexican-style hot sauce, but if you happen to make <a href="http://orangette.blogspot.com/2007/03/hot-sauce.html">this kind</a>, save the strained solids and use a spoonful in this dish.  They toast a little in the heat of the pan, and the resulting flavor is really <span>terrific</span>. We‚Äôve also used Tapati√≥, and it was very good too.</p>
<p>Olive oil<br />1 medium yellow onion, diced<br />1 tsp. ground cumin<br />¬Ω tsp. dried oregano<br />¬Ω tsp. Mexican-style hot sauce, or more to taste (this amount makes mild beans)<br />1 small (or ¬Ω medium) clove garlic, pressed<br />1 (15-ounce) can black beans<br />¬º tsp. salt, or to taste</p>
<p>Pour a glug of olive oil into a medium saucepan, and warm it over medium heat.  Add the onion, increase the heat to medium-high, and cook, stirring occasionally, until the onion is translucent and pale golden. It should be just starting to caramelize; it might scorch a bit in areas too, and that‚Äôs just fine.  Add the ground cumin and oregano, and stir well.  Add the hot sauce, and stir well again.  Add the garlic, followed by the beans and their can juices.  Reduce the heat to medium-low, and cook until the beans are soft and warmed through.  (Some brands of beans are softer than others; some will be ready as soon as they‚Äôre warm, but some need more time.)  Taste, and salt as needed.</p>
<p><span style="font-style:italic;">Note</span>: This recipe doubles easily. There‚Äôs no need to double the onion, though; one is plenty for two cans of beans.</p>
<p>Yield: 2 servings</p>
  </div>
